Datathon 2026 - Access to Care

This data analysis project explores the National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) Adult Summary Health Statistics dataset, provided by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

In this project, I explored and filtered out the data with FLAGs, indentify the topics, groups, and subgroups of interest, created data visualization using Tableau, and summarized my findings and recommendations.

Identifying Areas of Interest and Analysis

In this section, I explored different ways of grouping the dataset, including year, classification, topic, group, and subgroups. Using the taxonomy column, I found the topics that are the most relevant to this project. I made a separate Dataframe that includes just the topics and attributes of interest for analysis. I sorted the data in different ways to show the types of population that are most affected by each situation. Through these exploration, I identified the topics and groups that I would like to visualize in the next section.

Data Visualization: Tableau

In this section, I exported the dataframe and moved to Tableau to create data visualizations. I separated the data by group/subgroup and year (time period) to create two displays that show trends.

In[16]:
# export df_access csv

df_access.to_csv("Cleaned_Access_to_Care_Dataset.csv")

Dashboard 1: Separate By Group/Subgroup

In Tableau, I investigated the average of the following topics:

  • Delayed getting medical care due to cost among adults
  • Did not get needed medical care due to cost
  • Did not get needed mental health care due to cost
  • Did not take medication as prescribed to save money

Split by the subgroups under the following groups:

  • Age groups with 65 years and older
  • Race
  • Sex
  • Sexual orientation
  • Region
  • Employment status

From the visualization from Tableau, we found that in terms of healthcare:

  • Younger people have less access
  • Region-wise, the South has the least access, whereas the Northeast has the most access
  • Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander and Black and White have the least access, Asians have the most access
  • Man have more access than woman
  • Bisexuals have less access than straight or homosexual people
  • Part-time employees have the least access, and Not employed - Has never worked have the most access

Dashboard 2: Separate By Year

In Tableau, I also looked at the trend of healthcare access over the time period 2019-2024. I looked at the average of all groups, as well as separated each group and subgroup.

On average, access to health increased between 2019 and 2021, but then decrease after 2022 (more people reported health-access issues).

Key Findings, Recommendations, and Future Exploration

Here are the key findings from the Adult Summary Health Statistics dataset through data cleaning, exploration, analysis, and visualization:

1. Uninsured individuals under 65 years old experience the highest rates of delayed or unmet care (around 30%)
2. People who are young, Native Hawaiians/Pacific Islanders, female, bisexual, part-time employed, or living in the southern region are have the least access to healthcare.
3. Generally, access to healthcare increased from 2019 to 2021, but declined from 2022 to 2024. This may be related to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Recommendations to increase healthcare accessibility:

1. Develop or expend programs to support uninsured individuals under the age of 65. Target groups with the most limited healthcare access mentioned above. Potential programs could include:

  • Provide guidance to young individuals who may have just left their family's insurance plan to find a new plan that fits their needs.
  • Develop cultural specific insurance plans for Pacific Islanders. Provide multilingual service.
  • Include plans that support part-time employees who may not have insurance covered by their employer.

2. Invest in programs or infrastructure that can support communities with limited healthcare access, such as:

  • Provide care that emphasize inclusiveness for the LGBTQ+ community
  • increase the number of clinics, transportation to healthcare, or opportunites for telehealth services in the southern region

3. Investigate prepandemic and post-pandemic policy changes and develop a more sustainable healthcare system.

# plot by subgroup function (6 subplots)
import textwrap

def plot_by_subgroup(df, topic, groups):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(15, 20))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    for i in range(len(groups)):
        group  = groups[i]
        plot_df = df.loc[df["TOPIC"] == topic]
        plot_df = plot_df.loc[plot_df["GROUP"] == group,
                         ["SUBGROUP", "ESTIMATE"]].groupby("SUBGROUP", as_index=False)["ESTIMATE"].mean()
        plot_df["SUBGROUP_WRAP"] = plot_df["SUBGROUP"].apply(
            lambda x: "\n".join(textwrap.wrap(x, 12))
        )
        axes[i].bar(x=plot_df["SUBGROUP_WRAP"], height=plot_df["ESTIMATE"])

        axes[i].set_xlabel(group)
        axes[i].set_ylabel("Estimate Percentage")
        axes[i].set_title(f"Estimates by Subgroup for {group}")

        # axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', labelrotation=45)

    # plt.tight_layout()
    plt.tight_layout()
    # plt.title(f"Estimates by Group for {topic}")
    fig.suptitle("Topic: " + topic, fontsize=20)
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.93)
    plt.show()
